Java: use [numberOfLeadingZeros][1]. The classes Long and Integer have a nice set of utility functions.

    long commonPrefix(long x, long y) {
        return Long.numberOfLeadingZeros(x ^ y);
    }

On any algorithmic improvement: it would not be honest
to provide a superb solution here. And it is better
you work something out with pen and paper, puzzling the math side.
In fact I can see a tiny way. Maybe you can do even better.

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/10/docs/api/java/lang/Long.html#numberOfLeadingZeros(long)

Find the length of binary representation of both numbers, if its not the same then there can&#39;t be any matching bits, so only leading zeroes are the common prefix. Otherwise we can find the XOR value to find the number of matching prefix bits.

It&#39;s a neat trick, because the XOR operation will turn all the matching bits to zero until the left most bit that doesn&#39;t match. So, length of the common prefix will be the difference between total length of binary representation of either number(since they&#39;re the same length) and the length of the XOR value&#39;s binary representation.

Finally, since you want it for 62 bits, you have add leading zeroes, the number of leading zeroes is 62 minus length of either number&#39;s binary representation.

So,
62 - length of either number + common prefix.
Further simplification would mean the answer is 62 - length of xor value;

The only tricky case here if the numbers are same, you can handle that upfront.

```
int commonPrefix(int x, int y)
    if(x == y)
        return 62;

    int xLength = Math.floor(Math.log(x) + 1);
    int yLength = Math.floor(Math.log(x) + 1);
    
    if(xLength != yLength)
        return 62 - Math.max(xLength, yLength);

    int xor = x ^ y;
    int xorLength = Math.floor(Math.log(xor) + 1);

    return 62 - xorLength;
```


Once you&#39;ve got that covered a simple DFS should give you the ancestors of the node you&#39;re looking for and you can find the longest common prefix by comparing the given value with every ancestor.

I thought of a way which may be useful. You can modify the data in your node by adding an additional value for MSB bit set. For example, if number is 8, the MSB bit set, considering MSB is on left, is 62 - 4 = 58th bit from left. Also, you can store the bits in a **bitset**. So your tree node structure may be modified something like (in C++):
```
struct TreeNode
{
    int node_value;
    int set_msb_bit_from_left;
    bitset&lt;62&gt; b;
    TreeNode* left;
    TreeNode* right;
};
```
Important points:
1. Two numbers, x and y, have same `set_msb_bit_from_left` if they fall in same range [2^(n-1), 2^n). So such numbers can be added into one group, say `Gi` where `i` is the value of `set_msb_bit_from_left`.
2. If x belongs to `Gi` and y belongs to `Gi+1`, longest common prefix is `i`.
3. If x belongs to `Gi` and y belongs to `Gj` and `i &lt; j`, then longest common prefix is `i`.
4. If both x and y belong to same group, then bit-by-bit checking needs to be done starting from MSB to LSB until a mismatch is found, or some other efficient bit manipulation tricks like XOR operation.

Algorithm:
1. During creating nodes of tree, compute the `set_msb_bit_from_left` for the `node_value`.
2. &lt;s&gt;Create a data structure for storing groups based on `msb_bit_from_left`. This data structure can be a simple map or disjoint set union.&lt;/s&gt;
3. For given two nodes V (nth-level child) and X (ancestor), put all nodes from X to V in a set with comparator based on increasing `set_msb_bit_from_left` or group id.
4. Go from last (highest group id) to first element (lowest group id) in the set and compute longest common prefix between x and y:
- Get group for x and y.
- If same, process from MSB to LSB until a mismatch is found or do XOR of all belonging to same group and return the output.
- Else, return `min(grp_id_x, grp_id_y) - 1` where `grp_id_x`, `grp_id_y` are the respective `set_msb_bit_from_left` values. `-1` because we don&#39;t wanna count set MSB bit.

NOTE: if there are two or more elements from the last which are in the same group, then you just need to find longest common prefix between them (no need to process elements from other group, the longest common prefix will be smaller).

